{"_id":"70203390-4097-11eb-bdf6-dfe254ae95ac","postId":"2012_02_async-and-await-bb1cce3d-e706-3ecf-ab89-6f7945ef7d0f","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2012/02/async-and-await.html","replyTo":"bc76c9c0-408d-11eb-bd80-a1837e0753d5","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"When you're learning `async`, I recommend avoiding `async void` and always `await`ing your tasks. If you do that, then you won't have problems like a Console app exiting before its work is done.\r\n\r\nModern (.NET Core) Console apps can have an `async Task` `Main`; for older Console apps, you can call `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` once in the `Main` method.","date":"2020-12-17T18:41:13.326Z"}